<br>
The most depressing thing I see from some of these responses is the ignorance displayed by stereotyping all Christians as thinking, acting, or believing the same.  And yes, when you simply refer to 'them' as 'Christians', you are encompassing every Christian in that term.  <br>
<br>
But I can tell you that we are not all close minded bigots that think everything outside of a white picket fence world is evil.  In fact, most Christians that I know are free thinkers and quite tolerant in our views of the Bible and the world.  We don't run around trying to find fault with everything and accuse things we don't like as 'tools of the devil'.  No disrespect to Biblical references, but we are not all sheep.  In fact, I'm more of a cow.  :P<br>
<br>
Stereotyping all Christians under one view is just as ignorant as what you claim 'they' are doing to you.  I know many Christians that play EverQuest, and we enjoy the game immensely.  To think otherwise is just as narrowminded as any other stereotype, including the image you are accusing these fundamentalists of having about gamers.<br>
<br>
This only perpetuatates the cycle of ignorance.  I suggest you choose your terms more carefully.  Sorry, but this gets under my skin as much as those people that stereotype all 'Arabs' as terrorists, etc.<br>
<br>
I agree that this article has a number of errors, and this is quite popular among fundamentalist approaches to anything.  You can find fault in anything if you dig deep enough and conveniently ignore things that would prove you wrong.  Politicians do this, cults do this, the media does this *nods to Kaludram* and pretty much anyone that wants to perform some degree of brainwashing.  Repeat it enough, draw parallels to things that you know are already diskliked, and ignore anything good and you can convince the masses.  That doesn't mean there isn't a shred of truth in what you say, in fact most often you have to have at least a shred of truth to trigger an initial reaction.  The problem is that not all of the facts are presented for the reader to make a decision... the decision is already made for the reader.<br>
<br>
This is no different than any game review, movie review, or even opinion column.  Send someone from the &quot;Snooty Herald&quot; to see &quot;Austin Powers&quot; and it's going to get a bad review.  Send someone from &quot;The Man Show&quot; to see &quot;Chocolat&quot; and it will also get a bad review.  Have a fundamentalist Christian review EverQuest and what do you think you are going to get?  From the sound of some of the responses above, It seems you'd get just as slanted of a write up if you reviewed a game about exploring the world of the Bible. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#A62A2A>- </font><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie>Firiona Vie</a><font color=#A62A2A> - </font><a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4>The Soapbox</a> <font color=#A62A2A> - </font><a href="http://www.firionavie.org/">Firiona Vie</a><font color=#A62A2A> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 6.6.8<br>Copyright ©1999-2001 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  